      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Arsenic poisoning in Bangladesh is possibly one of the worst environmental disasters of our century (front page, Nov. 10). My expertise is in metal-related diseases, and a year ago I traveled through many villages in Bangladesh to study this poisoning.</p>
        <p>The situation is worse than it appears. I discovered countless subclinical cases in which people showed no physical symptoms, but they'll eventually become sick and die. If this were a sudden disaster like Chernobyl or Bhopal, local and international experts would instantly descend and work together. A well-coordinated group of experts must be drawn up. It's time to do something.</p>
        <p>BIBUDHENDRA SARKAR  Toronto, Nov. 12, 1998</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of biochemistry, University of Toronto.</p>
      </block>
